{
  "scenario": {
    "imagePrompt": "Um microtanque de laboratório com água turva, algas verdes, plantas aquáticas, caramujos e camarões pequenos. Ao lado, sensores simples de oxigênio, gás carbônico e amônia sobre a bancada.",
    "text": "No laboratório de restauração costeira, um microtanque com algas, caramujos e camarões precisa estabilizar até amanhã. A água piorou, e cada ajuste pode salvar ou estressar os animais.",
    "title": "O tanque que perdeu o ritmo"
  },
  "scenes": [
    {
      "dialogue": "{{NAME}}, o oxigênio caiu no meio da tarde, não de madrugada. O sensor de CO2 subiu, as algas estão verdes, e achei a luminária quase toda coberta por uma fita de etiqueta.",
      "imagePrompt": "Microtanque em bancada de laboratório. Luminária acima do tanque parcialmente coberta por uma fita opaca. Tela do sensor mostra “O2: 3 mg/L” e “CO2: alto”. Algas verdes visíveis, camarões perto da superfície.",
      "options": [
        {
          "feedback": "Isso encaixa. Sem luz disponível, as algas ficam sem energia para fabricar matéria orgânica e liberar oxigênio. Primeiro tiramos o bloqueio da luminária.",
          "isCorrect": true,
          "text": "Liberar a luz"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "Mais ração aumentaria restos na água e poderia piorar os resíduos. O sinal principal é a luminária bloqueada e o oxigênio caindo à tarde.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "Dar mais ração"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "O filtro pode importar depois, mas o CO2 alto com algas verdes e luz bloqueada aponta primeiro para falta de luz disponível.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "Trocar o filtro"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "Água mais fria pode segurar mais oxigênio, mas não explica a queda no horário de luz com a luminária coberta. Primeiro resolvemos a entrada de energia.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "Resfriar a água"
        }
      ],
      "question": "Qual ajuste deve vir primeiro?"
    },
    {
      "dialogue": "{{NAME}}, a luz voltou e o oxigênio subiu. Mesmo assim, os camarões estão parados e menores que o esperado. O registro mostra dois dias com ração zerada; eles ficam raspando o vidro como quem procura migalha.",
      "imagePrompt": "O mesmo microtanque com luminária ligada. Sensor mostra “O2: 7 mg/L”. Prancheta ao lado com registro simples: “Ração: 0 g” em dois dias seguidos. Camarões pequenos raspam o vidro; algas verdes nas laterais.",
      "options": [
        {
          "feedback": "Certo. Os camarões não fabricam seu próprio alimento com luz; precisam consumir matéria orgânica para obter energia e construir corpo.",
          "isCorrect": true,
          "text": "Falta de alimento"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "A luz já voltou e o oxigênio está bom. Para os camarões, a pista decisiva é a ração zerada por dois dias.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "Luz ainda baixa"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "Amônia baixa não deixa camarão fraco; é até desejável. O problema aqui é entrada de matéria orgânica para os consumidores.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "Amônia zerada"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "Algas demais poderiam incomodar, mas o registro de ração zerada explica melhor os camarões sem energia e sem crescimento.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "Algas demais"
        }
      ],
      "question": "O que explica melhor a fraqueza dos camarões agora?"
    },
    {
      "dialogue": "{{NAME}}, depois da reposição de ração, a água ficou leitosa. Há bolinhas sobrando no fundo e folhas mortas presas no canto. A bomba está girando, mas a amônia subiu rápido.",
      "imagePrompt": "Microtanque com água leitosa. No fundo há várias bolinhas de ração sobrando e folhas mortas acumuladas em um canto. Sensor na bancada mostra “Amônia: 1,5 mg/L”. Bomba com fluxo visível funcionando.",
      "options": [
        {
          "feedback": "Isso mesmo. Restos e folhas viram comida para micróbios, que liberam resíduos como amônia e ainda puxam oxigênio do tanque.",
          "isCorrect": true,
          "text": "Restos orgânicos"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "A luz pode mexer com algas, mas a pista forte são sobras no fundo, folhas mortas e amônia subindo mesmo com a bomba ligada.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "Luz forte"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "O fluxo aparece funcionando. Se fosse só bomba parada, não veríamos tanta sobra orgânica explicando a amônia.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "Bomba parada"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "Cascalho limpo não gera esse pico. O que está alimentando a bagunça são restos de matéria orgânica se decompondo.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "Cascalho limpo"
        }
      ],
      "question": "O que está sobrecarregando o tanque?"
    },
    {
      "dialogue": "{{NAME}}, sifonamos o fundo e a amônia caiu. O nitrato ainda encosta no limite, e a equipe precisa deixar uma rotina de fim de semana. Se faltar uma etapa, segunda-feira vira caldo de lagoa.",
      "imagePrompt": "Microtanque mais claro após limpeza, com sifão enrolado ao lado, pote pequeno de ração medida e luminária ligada. Tela mostra “O2: 7 mg/L”, “Amônia: 0,1 mg/L”, “Nitrato: 38/40 mg/L”. Cartão vazio de rotina na bancada.",
      "options": [
        {
          "feedback": "Perfeito. Luz sustenta os produtores, ração medida sustenta os consumidores, e o sifão remove matéria que viraria resíduos.",
          "isCorrect": true,
          "text": "Luz, ração medida, sifão"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "Só aumentar luz ajuda as algas, mas não alimenta os camarões nem remove resíduos. O tanque precisa de entradas e saídas equilibradas.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "Só luz mais forte"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "Ração livre vira sobra, micróbio feliz e amônia subindo. Os consumidores precisam de alimento, mas em dose que o sistema suporte.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "Ração livre diária"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "Sem retirada de resíduos, a matéria acumulada volta como nitrato e amônia. Tanque vivo não é cofre fechado de sujeira.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "Tanque sem trocas"
        }
      ],
      "question": "Qual rotina mantém o sistema mais estável até segunda?"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "scenario": {
    "imagePrompt": "A laptop on a shelter office desk showing an email campaign preview beside a browser window for the River Pets adoption fair shop. The browser address bar and link preview are large and readable, with a volunteer checklist nearby.",
    "text": "River Pets is about to send an adoption fair email. The preview links behave strangely, and bad clicks could cost donations and supply orders. Help the web team read each URL before launch.",
    "title": "The Link Before Launch"
  },
  "scenes": [
    {
      "dialogue": "{{NAME}}, the email test opens our sale page, but Chrome marks it Not secure and the payment widget stays gray. The path after the site name looks right, and the blast goes out in twenty minutes.",
      "imagePrompt": "Close-up of a browser address bar showing `http://shop.riverpets.org/fair/supplies`, with a visible “Not secure” warning. The page below shows a River Pets supply sale and a disabled gray “Pay” button.",
      "options": [
        {
          "feedback": "Yes. The beginning tells the browser which protocol to use. Switching to `https` keeps the same page target but gives the payment widget the secure connection it needs.",
          "isCorrect": true,
          "text": "Use `https`"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "Not first. The site name already reaches the right shop page. The security warning points to the start of the URL, so use `https`.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "Change site name"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "That would change filtered results, not the security warning. The better edit is to use `https` at the start.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "Add a filter"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "A fragment would jump within a page, but it will not fix an insecure connection. Use `https` instead.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "Add `#pay`"
        }
      ],
      "question": "Which URL edit should we make first?"
    },
    {
      "dialogue": "{{NAME}}, secure loads now, but the banner says “River Pet Gear Outlet,” and the cart has last year’s logo. The preview link has one tiny difference before `/fair/supplies`.",
      "imagePrompt": "Browser screen with address bar `https://shop.riverpet.org/fair/supplies`. Page banner reads “River Pet Gear Outlet” and shows old merchandise. A sticky note beside the monitor says “Official: shop.riverpets.org”.",
      "options": [
        {
          "feedback": "Right. That missing `s` sends the browser to a different site before it ever considers the page path.",
          "isCorrect": true,
          "text": "Use `riverpets.org`"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "The page path may be fine. The visible mismatch is before the first slash after `https://`, so the site name is the problem.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "Change `/fair`"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "A filter can change which items show, but it would not explain landing on a different outlet site. Use the correct site name.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "Add `?logo=new`"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "A section jump stays on the same page. This problem starts with the browser going to the wrong site, so fix the site name.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "Add `#top`"
        }
      ],
      "question": "Which part of the URL is sending clicks to the wrong place?"
    },
    {
      "dialogue": "{{NAME}}, the official site loads, but this version gives a 404. The working admin link is on the left; the email link is on the right. They match until the page name starts acting like a zipper missing a tooth.",
      "imagePrompt": "Split-screen browser comparison. Left address bar: `https://shop.riverpets.org/fair/supply-kits?pet=cat` with a normal product grid. Right address bar: `https://shop.riverpets.org/fair/supplykits?pet=cat` with a large “404 Page not found” message. The missing hyphen in `supplykits` is visually clear.",
      "options": [
        {
          "feedback": "Exactly. The browser is reaching the right site, but the page location after the site name does not match the real route.",
          "isCorrect": true,
          "text": "Fix page path"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "The connection is already secure. Changing `https` would not repair a missing page route.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "Change scheme"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "The official site name matches on both sides. The difference is in the page location after it.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "Swap domain"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "A fragment only points inside a loaded page. This page is not loading, so fix the path first.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "Add fragment"
        }
      ],
      "question": "What should we correct to stop the 404?"
    },
    {
      "dialogue": "{{NAME}}, the page finally opens, but the email for cat adopters shows only dog kits. The product count drops from 42 to 8 when the last part after the question mark is included.",
      "imagePrompt": "Browser showing `https://shop.riverpets.org/fair/supply-kits?pet=dog`. The page title says “Supply kits,” the filter chip says “Dog,” and a sidebar shows “Cat kits: 42” and “Dog kits: 8.”",
      "options": [
        {
          "feedback": "Yes. The part after `?` is filtering the same page. Setting `pet=cat` keeps the page but changes the results.",
          "isCorrect": true,
          "text": "Set `pet=cat`"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "That could move to a different page, but this page loads correctly. The wrong result set comes from the filter after `?`.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "Change `/fair`"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "Security is already working. The issue is not how the browser connects; it is which filtered results the page requests.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "Use `http`"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "A `#cat` jump would move within the loaded page, not request cat-filtered products. Set the query to `pet=cat`.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "Add `#cat`"
        }
      ],
      "question": "Which edit keeps the page but shows the right products?"
    },
    {
      "dialogue": "{{NAME}}, the “Schedule” link jumps to the right section, but our server log only records `/fair/day?pet=cat`. Changing the letters after `#` does not add a new request. We still need campaign tracking.",
      "imagePrompt": "Browser with address bar `https://shop.riverpets.org/fair/day?pet=cat#schedule` and the page scrolled to a “Schedule” section. Next to it, a simple server log panel shows one line: `GET /fair/day?pet=cat` with no `#schedule`.",
      "options": [
        {
          "feedback": "Right. If the server or analytics needs the value, put it in the query because the browser sends that with the request.",
          "isCorrect": true,
          "text": "Put in query"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "That is the tempting move, but the log shows the browser does not send the part after `#` to the server.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "Put in fragment"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "Changing the site would risk sending users somewhere else. The tracking detail belongs in the query on the same page.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "Change domain"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "Shortening the path might break the page. It also would not make the section label reach the server.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "Shorten path"
        }
      ],
      "question": "Where should the tracking value go so the server can see it?"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "scenario": {
    "imagePrompt": "A stadium entrance control table before an event, centered on a turnstile test laptop, a badge scanner with red and green lights, and a clipboard titled “Entry test outcomes.”",
    "text": "A stadium crew is testing badge scanners before gates open. The incident dashboard must count every possible swipe result once, or staffing and security estimates will be wrong.",
    "title": "Turnstile Test Before Doors"
  },
  "scenes": [
    {
      "dialogue": "{{NAME}}, the test rig caught a weird line: red scan light, but the arm unlocked. The draft has three boxes, and security will not love a missing corner case.",
      "imagePrompt": "A laptop screen shows a simple draft list titled “Swipe outcomes” with three boxes: “Green scan + arm unlocks,” “Green scan + arm stays locked,” and “Red scan + arm stays locked.” Beside it, a test photo shows a red scanner light and an unlocked turnstile arm.",
      "options": [
        {
          "feedback": "Yes. That red-light plus unlocked-arm result is possible in the evidence, and the sample space needs a place for it.",
          "isCorrect": true,
          "text": "Red, unlocks"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "That one is already listed. Adding it again would duplicate a result instead of filling the missing spot.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "Green, unlocks"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "Already covered. The missing result is the red-light case where the arm still unlocks.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "Green, stays locked"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "That one is also already listed. The evidence shows the other red-light outcome is missing.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "Red, stays locked"
        }
      ],
      "question": "Which outcome must be added to make the list complete?"
    },
    {
      "dialogue": "{{NAME}}, now the percentages look too chunky. One test line is sitting under two red tags, so the total can creep past one whole turnstile.",
      "imagePrompt": "A clean four-tile outcome grid for badge swipes. Columns are “Arm unlocks” and “Arm stays locked.” Rows are “Green scan” and “Red scan.” Two translucent labels overlap: “Red scan cases” covers the bottom row, and “Locked arm cases” covers the right column. The bottom-right tile is visibly covered by both labels.",
      "options": [
        {
          "feedback": "That tile belongs only to the locked-arm tag here, not both tags. The double-counted one is red scan with locked arm.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "Green, stays locked"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "That tile belongs only to the red-scan tag here. The overlap happens where red scan and locked arm meet.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "Red, unlocks"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "Right. It falls under both “Red scan cases” and “Locked arm cases,” so it cannot be counted twice as a separate outcome.",
          "isCorrect": true,
          "text": "Red, stays locked"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "That normal-looking tile is outside both red tags. It is not the source of the overlap.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "Green, unlocks"
        }
      ],
      "question": "Which result is being counted in two places?"
    },
    {
      "dialogue": "{{NAME}}, after we split the overlap, the counts finally total 20. The dashboard wants a probability from 0 to 1, not a raw count wearing a fake mustache.",
      "imagePrompt": "A dashboard table titled “Clean swipe tally, 20 tests.” Rows show: “Green + unlocks: 14,” “Green + stays locked: 3,” “Red + stays locked: 2,” and “Red + unlocks: 1.” A blank field reads “Normal entry probability: ___.”",
      "options": [
        {
          "feedback": "Correct. Normal entry is 14 out of 20, so the probability is 0.70 on the 0-to-1 scale.",
          "isCorrect": true,
          "text": "0.70"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "That is the count, not the probability. The dashboard needs 14 divided by the total 20, which is 0.70.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "14"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "A probability above 1 means something was overcounted or scaled wrong. The clean normal-entry value is 0.70.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "1.05"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "Probabilities cannot be negative. The clean count gives 14 out of 20, or 0.70.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "-0.15"
        }
      ],
      "question": "Which value should go in the normal entry probability field?"
    },
    {
      "dialogue": "{{NAME}}, doors open in ten minutes. The lead wants one final report that covers every swipe result once, including the awkward security one, without hiding it in a giant error bucket.",
      "imagePrompt": "A final report screen with four empty report rows and the same four outcome tiles visible beside it: green scan + unlocks, green scan + stays locked, red scan + stays locked, red scan + unlocks. A warning banner says “Rows must not overlap.”",
      "options": [
        {
          "feedback": "Yes. Pairing scan result with arm result gives every possible case one clear row, including the rare red-plus-unlocked case.",
          "isCorrect": true,
          "text": "Use outcome pairs"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "Dropping the rare row makes the report incomplete. Security needs that case visible, not erased.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "Drop rare row"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "Merging errors hides different problems together and can still blur what happened. The clean report needs one row per outcome pair.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "Merge all errors"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "Broad tags caused the overlap earlier. The safer move is to list the exact outcome pairs once each.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "Keep broad tags"
        }
      ],
      "question": "What reporting move fixes the sample space without creating a new counting problem?"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "scenario": {
    "imagePrompt": "A storm-damaged harbor pier at dawn with a warning siren pole, floating buoys in choppy water, a mooring rope tied to a cleat, a metal gate with a visible spring, and a small ground vibration monitor on the concrete.",
    "text": "A harbor crew must reopen a pier after a storm. Each warning signal works only if the right material carries the wave, and choosing wrong could send people back onto an unsafe dock.",
    "title": "Harbor Wave Check"
  },
  "scenes": [
    {
      "dialogue": "{{NAME}}, the buoy alarm tripped after that swell crossed the basin. The orange float bobbed up and down, but it did not ride all the way to the sensor like a tiny taxi.",
      "imagePrompt": "Close view of harbor water with a blue swell line moving toward a sensor post. An orange float is shown at two positions: lower and higher in the same spot, with a short vertical arrow. The sensor display reads “Alert: swell reached sensor.”",
      "options": [
        {
          "feedback": "Not this time. Air can carry sound, but the clue is the bobbing surface and the swell crossing the basin. The water is carrying this wave.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "Air"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "Yes. The water surface rises and falls while the swell moves across the basin, so water is the medium to watch before reopening.",
          "isCorrect": true,
          "text": "Water"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "The ground monitor is not the one changing here. The visible motion is in the water, so water is carrying the wave.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "Ground"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "The rope is nearby, but it is not the moving path in this clue. The swell is traveling through the water.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "Rope"
        }
      ],
      "question": "Which material carried the swell signal to the sensor?"
    },
    {
      "dialogue": "{{NAME}}, the loudspeaker test reached the dock office, but the spare siren inside the sealed service box was barely heard until we opened the lid. Same siren, very different path.",
      "imagePrompt": "A harbor service bench with two small sirens. One siren sits in open air with curved sound lines reaching a worker icon labeled “heard.” The other is inside a sealed clear box with faint sound lines and a note on the box reading “lid sealed.”",
      "options": [
        {
          "feedback": "Yes. The siren’s vibration needs air outside the speaker to carry the sound to people on the pier.",
          "isCorrect": true,
          "text": "Air"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "The box may sit on metal, but the clue is what changes when the lid opens. Restoring the air path restores the sound.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "Spring"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "Water carries swells, but this warning is a sound people hear. The needed path here is air.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "Water"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "The ground might carry rumbles, but the siren became clear when air could move. Air is the medium for this signal.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "Ground"
        }
      ],
      "question": "What medium must be open for the siren warning to reach people?"
    },
    {
      "dialogue": "{{NAME}}, I flicked the mooring line from the boat. The red tape on the rope snapped sideways and came back, while the kink ran to the cleat. The cleat sensor only sees that traveling kink.",
      "imagePrompt": "A taut mooring rope stretched from a small boat to a dock cleat. A visible kink in the rope is halfway along, moving toward the cleat with an arrow. A red tape mark on the rope is shown displaced sideways but still near its original position.",
      "options": [
        {
          "feedback": "Air may move around the rope, but the kink is traveling along the rope itself. The rope is the medium carrying this pulse.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "Air"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "Yes. The rope pieces wiggle locally while the pulse moves along the line to the cleat sensor.",
          "isCorrect": true,
          "text": "Rope"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "The boat floats on water, but the visible traveling kink is in the mooring line. The rope is carrying it.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "Water"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "The dock may shake later, but this signal is on the line before it reaches the cleat. The rope is the medium.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "Ground"
        }
      ],
      "question": "Which material is carrying the pulse toward the cleat sensor?"
    },
    {
      "dialogue": "{{NAME}}, the gate bumper still chatters after the latch shuts. A tight bunch of coils travels down the shiny spring, but the painted coil ends up back where it started.",
      "imagePrompt": "A metal harbor gate latch with a horizontal shiny spring bumper. Several spring coils are compressed close together near the middle with an arrow moving right. One painted yellow coil is shown slightly shifted but aligned with a ghost mark of its original spot.",
      "options": [
        {
          "feedback": "The gate frame matters for support, but the traveling bunch is inside the coil assembly. The spring is carrying this vibration.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "Gate frame"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "Yes. The compression moves along the spring while each coil only shifts and returns, like a tiny metal accordion with manners.",
          "isCorrect": true,
          "text": "Spring"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "Air could carry the chattering sound, but the visible moving compression is in the spring. That is the medium for this wave.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "Air"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "The ground is not where the bunched coils are traveling. The spring is the material carrying the pulse.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "Ground"
        }
      ],
      "question": "Which part is carrying the traveling compression?"
    },
    {
      "dialogue": "{{NAME}}, before the next siren test, the concrete sensor spiked when the forklift crossed the lot. The water stayed calm, and the microphone barely moved. We have ten minutes before visitors line up.",
      "imagePrompt": "Concrete pier floor with a forklift in the background and a ground vibration monitor in the foreground. The monitor graph shows a tall spike labeled “ground motion.” Nearby, a microphone graph is nearly flat and the harbor water surface is smooth.",
      "options": [
        {
          "feedback": "The microphone trace is nearly flat, so air sound is not the main warning here. The spike points to ground motion.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "Air path"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "The water is calm in the evidence, so a water wave does not explain the spike. The ground carried the vibration.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "Water path"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "Yes. The concrete motion reached the sensor through the ground, so hold the reopening until the vibration limit is checked.",
          "isCorrect": true,
          "text": "Ground path"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "The rope is not involved in this reading. The sensor spike matches vibration traveling through the concrete ground.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "Rope path"
